Germany, year zero
May 8 always reminds me of 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was truly a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived on our small street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great slaughter was coming to an end.
My father, a resistor, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
This was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have some volumes of romantic poetry recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen. The occupation armies were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to get food.
My father was transported directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and charged with setting up - from nothing - the city’s energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, even if for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But what for?
For what future?
"You must help," my mother said to me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card as a "victim of fascism," while others wore a Cross of Honor obtained for late service to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, almost everyone mourned the loss of loved ones.
Yet, this phase did not last.
It is almost unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and especially accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and detainees.
On the other hand, after a short period of no-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
A year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not just empty talk, and it relied on German traditions.
Of course, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
This was also the beginning of the Cold War, and everyone wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two particular lessons deserve mention.
The first is economic in nature, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy certainly takes root more easily in an economic recovery context.
This requires above all initiative on the part of individuals who are eager to end a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with an initial capital.
That is why the American support through the Marshall Plan was so important.
Similarly, the European Union helped the formerly communist countries and continues to accompany them in their journey.
The other lesson, one of morality, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders beyond dispute.
However, Germany did not undertake its long path by worrying about the past.
In fact, many have described the years after 1949 under Adenauer as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in position.
In a way, the country ignored its past to move forward into the future.
Years later, after establishing a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced its past, with great success.
The Nazi past is unique in horror, and comparisons with other wounded countries thus lead to confusion.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first novelty, then an attempt to confront the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an occasion to look back at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn toward the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
